  data-post-positive="104"
  data-post-id="25927785" data-poster-id="82819" id="comment-25927785">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="neodorian"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=82819&amp;sid=d9d69166ba93051bb71e5d6749285fea">neodorian</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Scholae Palatinae</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/12/snowden-speaks-from-moscow-the-missions-already-accomplished/?comments=1&post=25927785#comment-25927785" title="2013-12-26T16:48:17-06:00" class="timeago datetime">Thu Dec 26, 2013 4:48 pm</a>
        
          <span class="highlight reader-fav">Reader Fav</span>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25927551#p25927551" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Scorpiuscat</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I still cannot believe that there is not rioting over this, it amazes me how little the general public seems to care. <br /><br />I often wondered how a society could get to the point that we see in the George Orwell's 1984 and now I know....sad, just really sad.</div><br /><br />Semi-related but we often mention how the audience of Ars (or other sites with similar readerships) doesn't always see things from the same angles as the rest of the country.  *I* can see why it's messed up when federal agencies with little to no oversight are able to circumvent (or in some cases, straight up &quot;hack&quot; into) private servers and communication networks but people sitting at home watching the news might not.<br /><br />I just spent the Christmas holidays with family out in the rural US and we found ourselves watching the local TV news.  This isn't something I normally do so I hadn't really seen how bad it is.  The talk was all about this &quot;traitor&quot; and how he is selling out our secrets to foreigners.  They even used the &quot;bad guy&quot; filters on his video so everything looked dark and menacing.  At first I was thinking &quot;wow, this is crazy how obviously spun this is.&quot;  Then my girlfriend's dad mumbled something about how they ought to just shoot the bastard and I realized how successfully the domestic PR has been portraying their angle.  Her dad is a guy who doesn't like the government and complains about the feds all the time.  Still, when you see the guy with all of the usual TV cues of dark, ominous music, video filters, and familiar &quot;villain&quot; language, you realize how much of the story is seen differently by a huge part of the population.<br /><br />Not saying the online or techie community is free from spin or bias.  We have our own interests and they color the way we see things.  Still, to watch something on the regular evening news (not the typical cable &quot;news&quot; opinion shows) and see how the story is being told to the &quot;rest of the country&quot;, it was made very clear why a lot of us aren't all that upset.  To them it's the story of a black-hat traitor selling our military secrets to foreigners who would use them against us.  There is no doubt in their minds that this guy is bad news and that we ought to go give him hell for America.
      
        <p class="edited">Last edited by <a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=82819&amp;sid=d9d69166ba93051bb71e5d6749285fea">neodorian</a> on Thu Dec 26, 2013 4:49 pm</p>
      
    </div>
