    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25927551#p25927551" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Scorpiuscat</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I still cannot believe that there is not rioting over this, it amazes me how little the general public seems to care. </div><br /><br /><br />I've said it before, and I'll say it again: we've gotten where we are because the public at large DOESN'T care; they're too wrapped up in their iPhones, Kardashians, and Starbucks lattes.  Nothing is going to come of this, because a) the public doesn't care, b) will elect those who say they'll take care of them and don't have to worry about anything, and c) people these days just don't have a clue what privacy means.<br /><br />Facebook, Google, Twitter, Pinterest, LinkedIn, FourSquare, Instagram, Snapchat, Tumblr, Flickr, MySpace, LiveJournal, CafeMom...  these are just the obvious ones that require ZERO thought on anyone's part.  Consider deep-packet inspection by major cable providers; consider all the hops your unencrypted email goes through; consider all those unencrypted texts, tweets, and TwitPics blasting out to the world for anyone to see AND SELL (looking at you, Twitter).<br /><br />It's easy.  It's fun.  It's &quot;safe&quot;: what could possibly happen?  It's not like someone can post a picture of me hooking up with my married girlfriend at a Starbucks on the other wide of town, amirite?
      
    </div>
